{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_limbo_ver01/data/sn85025570/00383348407/1938012701/0040.xml":{"full_text":"SIXTY-NINTH YEAR\nVoters Will Elect\n13 Officials in \u20193B\nSTADIUM FUND\nREACHES $1,020\nA fine response in the drive for\nthe city\u2019s share of funds for a\nstadium at Memorial Field is re\nported by high school alumni teams\nselling athletic events tickets at\n$lO for 30 games, proceeds to go\nto the fund. By Wednesday after\nnoon 102 tickets had been sold,\nbringing the total to $1,020. The\ngoal is $2,500.\nMasons Plan\nConstitution\nDay Service\nRANDGAARD HONORED\nAT STATE MEETING;\nOLD MEMBERS COMING\nIn celebration of' the one hun\ndred fiftieth anniversary of the\nadoption of the Masonic constitu\ntion, members of Redwood Falls\nMasonic bodies will hold Consti\ntution day ceremonies Wednesday\nevening, February 16.\nRalph Stanford of Willmar,\nstate grand master, will be here\nand the principal speaker will be\nJohn I. Davis of Benson.\nOscar G. Randgaard, worship\nful master of the Blue lodge here,\nreturned Thursday from St. Paul\nwhere he delivered the lecture\nand conducted the work for the\nthird degree in the state school of\ninstruction. While there he con\ntacted Julius A. Schmahl, former\nsecretary of state and treasurer\nand once a resident here. Sch\nmahl promised that, weather per\nmitting, he and his brother Her\nman would come here for the\ncelebration.\nHerman Schmahl is the oldest\nliving member of the Masonic\norder here, having been accepted\nto membership in 1882. A. C.\nSchmahl of Redwood Falls enter\ned the Masons in 1883 and Julius\nis also an old member. They twill\nbe honored at the festivities.\nLodges from Springfield, Lam\nberton, Walnut Grove, Sanborn,\nFairfax, Morton, Olivia, Bird\nIsland, Renville, Marshall and\nCottonwood, will be invited.\nRedwood Men\nGiven Offices\nBRECKENRIDGE, LAU\nCHOSEN ON BREEDER,\nSEED GROUP BOARDS\nStanley Breckenridge of Red\nwood Falls was elected vice-pre\nsident of the state Spotted Poland\nChina Breeders association for the\nfourth time during Farm and\nHome work at University farm\nlast week.\nAnother Redwood county man\nhonored at the event was H. C.\nLau of Tracy who was named to\nthe board of directors of the new\nMinnesota Hybrid Seed Growers\nassociation.\nAmong those from this com\nmunity who attended Farm and\nHome week were Miss Lenore\nGolden, J. I. Swedberg. Mrs. Otto\nFlom of Belview, H. O. Draeger\nand Forrest Crocker of Morgan,\nMrs. Robert Bellig of Wabasso,\nMrs. H. A. Winn of Seaforth, Ver\ngie Trent of Delhi, Au Della\nThompkins of Sherman ar.d Jos\neph Zeug and Harrison Schmeis\ning Jr. of Lucan.\nGEORGE NORCUTT\nOF LUCAN BURIED\nFATHER OF SIX CHIL\nDREN DIES SUDDENLY\nAT TRACY HOSPITAL\nLucan\u2014Funeral services were\nheld here Wednesday for George\nNorcutt, 34, who died very sud\ndenly at the Tracy hospital Sun\nday afternoon after an illness of\nfour days. Burial was in the\nLucan cemetery.\nHe was born at Lucan, January\n17, 1904, the son of Mr. and Mrs.\nR. A. Norcutt. August 13, 1924 he\nmarried Miss Violet Klante. They\nwere the parents of six children,\nthree girls, Carolyle, Betty Lou,\nand Darlys and three boys, Calvin,\nDelwood and Gene. His parents\nand five brothers. Chester of\nRedwood Falls, Leslie, Stanford,\nKenneth and Quentin and three\nsisters, Mrs. Jay Dickerson of Ap\ntos, California, Mrs. Dale Korems\nof Minneapolis and Mrs. Walter\nAnderson of Lucan also survive.\nThe pall bearers were brothers\nin law, Galen Dunne, Clarence\nKlante, Roland Klante, William\nKlante, Hans Larsen and Elmer\nBrandt\nGet Store Job\nLang and Mahal of Redwood\nFalls received the contract for\nbuilding W. R. Wingate\u2019s store at\nOlivia at a letting held Monday.\nIt is expected that work on the\nstructure will begin next week.\nIt will be similar to the Big Store\nthere which recently burned.\nr \u00abUl Kip\n\nTHE REDWOOD GAZETTE\nPOLITICS IS POPULAR\nCONVERSATION TOPIC:\nNO FILINGS YET\nAlthough there have been no\nfilings in Redwood county as yet,\nthere is considerable discussion of\npossible candidates wherever\ngroups gather.\nCounty voters will go to the\npolls in June and November to\nnominate ar.d elect 13 officials, in\ncluding a district judge, a state\nsenator and two representatives.\nOfficers whose terms expire this\nyear are: District judge\u2014Albert\nH. Enersen of Marshall who ser\nves the ninth judicial district in\ncluding Redwood, Brown, Nicollet,\nLyon ar.d Lincoln counties.\nState Senator\u2014Frank F. Rom\nberg of the fourteenth legislative\ndistrict comprised of Brown and\nRedwood counties.\nRepresentative-at-large John\nM. Zwach who serves Brown and\nRedwood counties in the state leg\nislature.\nRepresentative\u2014From Redwood\ncour.ty. This position has been\nvacant since the death of H. M\nAune.\nCounty Auditor\u2014lra R. Rogers.\nCounty Treasurer \u2014A. P. Falk.\nRegister of Deeds\u2014E. H. Bol\nlum.\nSheriff\u2014L. J. Kise.\nCounty Attorney\u2014George A.\nBarnes.\nCounty Superintendent of\nSchools\u2014C. D. Clipfell.\nCoroner\u2014Dr. J. Gordon Cole.\nCounty Commissioner Second\nDistrict\u2014Herman Beckman.\nCounty Commissioner Fourth\nDistrict\u2014E. A. Pease.\nElective officers whose terms\ndo not expire this year are Clerk\nof Court Frank Baldwin, Judge of\nProbate R. V. Ochs and Com{niss\nioners Phillip Raveling, Herman\nMuetzel and J. P. Kragh.\nFilings may be made until\nsometime in May, the date not yet\nset. Fees are $lO.\n3 County Girls\nGet Club Jobs\nACCEPT POSITIONS AS\nCOUNTY LEADERS IN\n4-H ACTIVITIES\nThree Redwood cotin ty girls\nprominent in 4-H club activities,\nhave accepted positions as club\nleaders in Minnesota counties. At\npresent all are students at the\nUniversity of Minnesota. They\nwill begin their six months terms\nabout April 1.\nCatherine Winn, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. H. A. Winn of Sea\nforth. will have her headquarters\nat Stillwater in Washington\ncounty. Only 18 and in her Fresh\nman year at the university, she is\nthe youngest 4-H club leader in\nthe state.\nChanging from Lac Qui Parle\ncounty. Margaret Gunnelson, dau\nghter of Mr. a- d Mrs. J. S. Gun\nnelson of Belview, will work at\nThief River Falls in Pennington\ncounty this year.\nMiss Kathleen Flom, popular\n4-H club leader in Nobles county,\nhas accepted the post as director\nof club activities there for the\nthird time. She is a former Bel\nview girl.\nHer acceptance of the position\nwad given County Agent C. E.\nStower during Farm and Home\nweek after he conveyed, to her the\ninvitation of the county extension\ncommittee.\nDr. W. A. Brand attended a\nstate board of health meeting at\nthe University of Minnesota Tues\nday.\nSee World From Different Levels\nA. W. Bertke of Sioux City, i\nwho measures six feet and seven 1\ninches in his sox, had some dif- j\nficulty explaining the mechanism\nof the self-serve popcorn mach-\nmes, which he sells, to E. O. 1\n\u201cGene\u201d Charlebois and Clare I\nWork Underway on .Stadium Project\nDespite the cold wave, work\nwas progressing steadily on the\nMemorial Field stadium project\nthis week. WPA workers are\nshown loading stone from the old\n93 More Phones in\nDirectory Just Out\nFire Destroys\nFarm Dwelling\nAt Lamberton\nHOUSE CONSUMED IN\nSHORT TIME, FLAME\nWHIPPED BY WIND\nLamberton \u2014Driven by the high\nwind early Monday morning, fire\ndestroyed the farm home occu\npied by Mr. and Mrs. Sam Minor\nwith all their household goods\nand clothing.\nThe house was on the Ham\nmond estate farm, three miles\nnorthwest of Lamberton, and was\n,o have been vacated soon by the\nIvlinor family who are moving to\nStaples. It was to have been ocs\nby the Arthur Nachtman\nfamily, also of this community.\nThe Minors had arisen early\nand started fires with cobs in two\nstoves. An overheated stovepipe\nis believed to have set fire to the\nhouse. As there was no telephone\nat the place, no help came until\nnames were leaping high in the\nair and could be seen for miles\naround. The Minors and their\nfour children had time only to\nrush to safety, the fire progressed\nso rapidly.\nAfternoon Meeting\nof PTA Planned\nA meeting of the Parent Teach\ner association will be held Mon\nday at 2:30 in the Lincoln audi\ntorium. The rhythm band from\nMiss Virginia Guernsey\u2019s room\nwill open the program; there will\nbe community singing directed by\nMrs. E. A. Johnson and the re\ngular business session will fol\nlow. Carrying out the theme\n\u201cParent Meet Teacher,\u201d those who\nattend will be given an opportu\nnity to visit classrooms and discuss\nmutual problems with the teach\ners.\nPatrick Kohler of Mission,\nTexas visited a few days last week\nat the L. J. Schottenbauer home.\nHouck. Bertke looked over the\ntop and pointed down into the\nmachine, recently installed at\nLauterbach\u2019s, while Hauck and\nCharlebois needed stepladders.\nThey had their inning, however,\nwhen he had to stoop to show\nthem other parts of the machine.\nREDWOOD FALLS, MINNESOTA, THURSDAY, JANUARY 27, 1938\nhigh school foundations on Min\nnesota street and Broadway and\nunloading them at the stadium\nsite where they will be used in\nthe new structure.\n897 TELEPHONES NOW\nLISTED IN REDWOOD\nFALLS EXCHANGE\nA net gain of 93 subscribers by\nthe Redwood County Rural Tele\nphone company and Tri-State\nTelephone and Telegraph com\npany brings the list of telephones\nserviced by the two organizations\nin this vicinity to 2198.\nThe new telephone book which\nis being distributed this week is\nlittle different from that of last\nyear which listed 2105 numbers.\nIt contains the same number of\nDages, 40 including covers. Blue\nink is used on the cover instead\nof brown, as on the 1937 directory.\nIt was printed by the Gazette.\nLargest in the book, the Red\nwood Falls exchange which in\ncludes rural, North Redwood and\nDelhi patrons, shows an increase\nof 34 this year. There are 8\nphones listed. Walnut Grove\nnext with 339 phones, five over\nlast year and other exchanges in\ncluded in the directory are Bel\nview, Echo, Morgan, Vesta, Wa\nbasso and Wood Lake, serviced\nthrough the rural company.\nAs usual the \u201cS\u201d divisions of the\nbook are the longest in every\ntown but Vesta. Two hundred\nseventy names listed in the book\nbegin with S, 108 of them in the\nRedwood Falls exchange. B is the\nnext most popular last initial in\nthe territory with 194 listed. .In\nVesta B takes precedence over S.\nThere are no X divisions and\n(Continued on page five)\nCOOK RE-ELECTED\nTO FIELD BOARD\n$1,512 PAID FOR WORK\nAT FIELD, ANNUAL\nREPORT SHOWS\nRichard Cook was re-elected. a\ndirector of the Redwood Falls Re\ncreational association at the an\nnual meeting of stockholders in\nthe city hall Thursday night. He\nhas a four year term.\nOnly a handful of stockholders\nattended, but 151 shares of Mem\norial Field stock were represented\nby person and proxy.\nThe financial report, presented\nby Reede Gray, secretary, show\ned that receipts, including last\nyear\u2019s balance of $675.40 amount\ned to $1,637.79 to January 1. They\ndo not include proceeds from\nathletic events, but are largely\nmade up of payments on stock\nbought two years ago.\nDisbursements for moving the\nband shell, tools for WPA labor\nand expert supervision of con\nstruction of the concrete tennis\ncourts and trucking amounted to\n$1,512.28. The association\u2019s bal\nance as of January 1 was $125.51.\nCook\u2019s election to the board of\ndirectors must be ratified by the\ncity council. As soon as that\nmove is made the board will\nelect its officers.\nRedwood Men Attend Last\nMan\u2019s Club Get Together\nLeo Barrett, candy maker at<\nLauterbach\u2019s and Myron Wigen of\nthe Holm berg Chevrolet company,\nattended a reunion of \u201cF\u201d battery\nof the old World War Rainbow\ndivision in Minneapolis Saturday\nnight Y\nThe battery has a \u201cLast Man\u2019s\u201d\nclub patterned after that at Still\nwater. The wine that the last\nthree survivors will quaff is now\nencased in a 75 nun. sMI, the\nlast one the battery fired in the\nwar. Engraved on the \u00abh\u00bbli are\nall the names of battery members\nand inside it are letters from\nGeneral Leach and the French\nGeneral Gourand.\nOf the original 200 members,\nall but about a dozen survive as\nthe battery was perhaps the most\nfortunate in die war. Only three\nInstitute To\nBring State\nFarm Experts\nFREE LUNCH PLANNED\nEACH DAY; MARCH\n9 AND 10 CHOSEN\nState specialists in farm and\nhome projects and problems are\nscheduled to speak at a Farmer\u2019s\nInstitute to be held in the new\nRedwood Falls High school audi\ntorium March 9 and 10.\nA varied and informative pro\ngram has been tentatively arrang\ned by the county agent\u2019s office in\nco-operation with the Civic and\nCommerce association which is\nsponsoring the event.\nSpeakers for the first day will\nprobably include Parker Ander\nson, forester with the University\nof Minnesota extension division,\nwho will discuss windbreaks; H.\nL. Parten, state entomoligist, who\nhas surveyed the situation in Red\nwood county and will speak on\ngrasshoppers and insect pests and\nSkuli Rutford of University Farm\nwho will outline the 1938 soil con\nservation program.\nFarm women using electricity\nfor the first time this year will be\ninterested in hearing Miss Victoria\nHarris of REA who will demon\nstrate household electrical ap\npliances.\nTentative arrangements for the\nsecond day\u2019s program include the\nselection of L. M. Stahler of the\nstate weed farm at Lamberton to\ndiscuss the latest information on\nthe destruction of creeping jenny\nand other noxious weeds. Dr. W.\nL. Boyd of University Farm will\ntalk on sleeping sickness in horses\nand Berry H. Akers, editor of the\nFarmer magazine, will discuss the\nbusiness outlook for 1938.\nMiss Orrjne Johnson, fashion\neditor of the Farmer\u2019s Wife will\ntalk on \u201cSpring Fashion Trends\nof 1938.\u201d Miss Johnson is in New\nYork now but will return in time\nfor the institute.\nFree lunches will be served at\nnoon both days for the conven\nience of those attending the all\nday sessions. A or.e day institute\nwill be held at Lamberton March\n7.\nSub-District\nMeet Will Be\nBrought Here\nPOSSIBILITY BOTH OF\nPLAY-OFFS WILL BE\nSTAGED IN CITY\nAlthough not previously slated\nas the scene of sub-district bask\netball tournaments this year, Red\nwood Falls will be host I to one\nsub-district event and it is possi\nble that both tournaments will be\nheld here.\nAt a meeting of school superin\ntendents in Belview last Wednes\nday, it was voted to hold the west\nern section sub-district here in\nstead of at Walnut Grove as pre\nviously planned. Walnut Grove,\nEcho, Delhi, Wabasso and Bel\nview will meet in the contest the\nweek of February 28.\nSince announcement of the\nschoolmen\u2019s decision, Morton,\nFranklin and Morgan of the\neastern sub-district conference\nhave asked to have their tourna\nment held here rather than at\nWinthrop as scheduled.\nThe question will be taken up\nat a meeting of superintendents\nfrom those towns and Gaylord,\nGibbon and Winthrop with Sup\nerintendent Reede Gray here to\nnight. The eastern half tourney\nwill be run off March 3, 4 and 5.\nIn other years all the small\nschools competed in one sub-dis\ntrict meet.\nRedwood Fails will have the\ndistrict basketball tournament in\nthe new high school gymnasium\nMarch 10, 11 and 12, the Cardinals\ncompeting against New Ulm,\nSpringfield, Sleepy Eye, Fairfax,\nLamberton and winners in the\ntWO SUb-district events.\ngets the regional tourney March\n18 and 19 and the state playoff\nwill be held in University field\nhouse, Minneapolis, March 24, 25\nand 26.\nMrs. D. W. Gold was hostess to\nthe members of her Birthday club\nMonday evening when Mrs. C. A.\nHillig was the guest of honor.\nmen were killed in action.\nBattery members ascribe their\nfortune to an alert spirit fostered\nby their old captain Art Gow, a\nformer University of Minnesota\ncheer leader, who came from\nPhiladelphia far the meeting.\n\u201cDaddy\u201d Brooks, another member\nwho returned is now sales man\nager for Wrigley\u2019s in Chicago.\nThe reunion was held in a hall\non Lake street with 86 former\nwar buddies present Both Bar\nrett and Wigen saw comrades\nthey had not seen for 20 years.\nWigen was instrument sergeant\nwith the battery and Barrett was\na corporal. Wigen was listed as\na casualty at the dose of the war\nbut Barrett served with the com\npany in the Army of Occupation.\nCold Grips Section\nIn Wake of Freak\n\u201cSnowless Blizzard\u201d\nAirplane Damaged in High Wind\nThe fierce wind which howled\nthrough Redwood county Monday\nnight wrecked the airplane be\nlonging to Joseph Trost of Sea\nforth which was staked to the\nRedwood and Renville\nLead in Corn Acreage\n100 OFFICIALS TO\nATTEND FIRE MEET\nPROTECTION OF FARMS\nTO BE DISCUSSED\nBY STATE MEN\nAbout 100 township and village\nofficials are expected to attend a\nmeeting to discuss means of giv\ning fire protection to outlying\nvillages and townships. The meet\ning has been definitely set for 8\np. m. Friday, February 4 in the\nRedwood Falls city hall.\nFrank Yetka, state fire marshal\nand Arthur D. Nordstrom, deputy\ncommissioner of insurance and\ndeputy fire marshal, will be\nspeakers. Refreshments will be\nserved.\nAll township and village offic\nials interested are invited by the\nRedwood Falls fire department\ncommittee which includes O. G.\nRandgaard, R. F. Byram and Chris\nSchulte.\nLamberton\nPlays Cards\nHere Friday\nSLEEPY EYE DEFEATED\nWEDNESDAY 34 TO 16;\nJUNIORS DROP TILT\nRedwood Falls\u2019 Cardinals will\nplay their second game of the\nweek Friday night when they\nmeet the strong Lamberton aggre\ngation here at the new high school\ngym. The Lambs have made\nrapid strides after a slow start\nand are going strong. From all\nindications the game will be no\nset-up.\nThe Cardinals had comparative\nly easy going Wednesday evening\nwhen they defeated the Sleepy\nEye Indians 34 to 16 here. Coach\nZimmerman used 10 men against\nthe Indians. Duea was high score\nman with 12 points.\nThe Cardinals got off to an 8-1\n'lead with two free throws by\nDuea, a bucket by Dickmeier, two\nfield goals by Hoffman and one\nfrom under the hoop shot by\nDuea. The Indians countered\nwith free throws by Wohlford\nand Johnson. Duea swished the\nnet twice more and Hoffman made\na free toss. On a side shot, John\nson connected and the first quart\ner ended with Redwood leading\n13 to 6.\nLussenhop scored twice from\nthe floor and Albrecht and Sch\nmidt counted for the Indians.\nSleepy Eye made a free toss and\nFischer scored a field goal after\nwhich Tommy Crooks broke into\n(Continued on page eight)\nMrs. Howard Sanders\nUndergoes Operation v\nMrs. Howard P. Sanders un\nderwent an operation for rvip\ntured appendix in St. Petersburg,\nFlorida, Wednesday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Parker D. Sanders\nleft the same day by train from\nOlivia for Chicago where they\ntook a plane. They will arrive in\nSt Petersburg this afternoon.\nOnly information received is that\nMrs. Sanders is doing as well as\nmay be expected.\nMr. and Mrs. Leroy Buhner and\nMiss Viola BHlie visited at the C.\nE. Shoemaker home at Marshall\nSunday evening.\nNOTlCE\u2014Associated Press\nette readers starting with the\niasne of Febraary S will sat\nbe carried before the Feb\nruary 17 or 24 \u2019tone. 1\nground near Memorial Field. Both\ntoings were crumpled, causing\ndamage estimated between \"JSOO\nand S6OO. The plane of Jack Rob\ninson at the left was bounced\nabout but escaped damage.\nRANK NINETEENTH;\nTWENTIETH IN U. S\u201e\nCENSUS SHOWS\nRedwood and Renville counties\ndevote more acreage to corn than\nany other counties in Minnesota\naccording to the 1935 government\ncensus figures just released at\nWashington.\nWith 145,172 acres planted to\ncorn in 1934, Redwood county was\nnineteenth in the\" nation in com\nacreage while Renville county\nwith 145,157 acres, ranked twen\ntieth.\nStrangely enough, Redwood\ncounty advanced from forty-sev\nenth place and Renville from fif\nty-second place in 1929 figures\nalthough both planted less com\nin 1934 than in 1929. The \u2019para\ndox is believed due to the fact\nthat *many other localities were\ndisastrously affected by drouth\nthat year.\nThe average farm reporting\nfrom Redwood county in 1929\nplanted 60 acres of com for a\ntotal com acreage of 155,973. In\nRenville county the average farm\nreporting planted 50 acres of com\nfor a total acreage that year of\n151,811. In 1934 the average com\nacreage per farm in Redwood\ncounty was 55, in Renville 48.\nMartin county ranked twenty\nthird in 1934 and fifty-sixth in\n1929, Nobles county twenty-ninth\nand sixty-eighth and Jackson\ncounty thirty-ninth in 1934. It\nwas not among the first 100 in\n1929.\nMcLean county, Illinois, led all\ncounties in com acreage, advanc\ning from second place in 1929,'\nreplacing Custer county, Nebras\nka, which was not among the first\n100 counties in 1934, the decrease*\nbeing attributed largely to the\nsevere drouth.\nLivingston, Iroquois, and La-\nSalle counties, Illinois, occupied\nsecond, third and fourth places;\nPottawattomie, lowa, fifth; and\n(Continued on page five)\nMrs. Guldan\nBuried Friday\nFORMER RESIDENT OF\nMORGAN COMMUNITY\nDIED AT NEW ULM\nClements\u2014Funeral services for\nMrs. Anna Guldan, 80, who died\nlast Tuesday at Loretto hospital,\nNew Ulm, were held at 9:30 a. m.\nFriday at the New Ulm Catholic\nchurch. Burial was beside her\nhusband there.\nMrs. Guldan had spent the\nwinter with relatives at Clem\nents and was at the home of her\na daughter Mrs. Frank Walter\nwhen she suffered a stroke two\nweeks ago.\nShe was bom in Austria, Aug\nust 10, 1857, the daughter of Mr.\nand Mrs. Anton Forster. She\ncame to the United States 53\nyears ago and settled at New Ulm\nwhere she lived for 18 years. She\nthen moved to a farm near Mor\ngan and the family returned to\nNew Ulm in September 1915.\nHer husband Wenzel Guldan,\na daughter, Mrs. Charles Weyker\nand a son Wenzel Guldan Jr., pre\nceded her in death. Survivors\nare Mrs. Walter, Mrs. Albert\nKempfert and Mrs. Joe Seifert,\nall of Clements and two sons,\nGeorge of Walnut Grove and John\nof New Ulm. There are 14\ngrandchildren and two great\ngrand children.\nSecond REA Line\nAlmost Completed\nLines of Redwood county\u2019s sec\nond REA project of about 100\nmiles will probably be energized\nnext week. At present the con\ntractor is waiting for transformers\nand other needed equipment and\nas soon as they arrive \u201cjuice\u201d will\n1. turned OCL I\nNUMBER 31\nWINTER MONTHS DRIER\nTHAN USUAL; 1937\nMOISTURE NORMAL\nSouthwestern Minnesota was\nstill gripped firmly in the clasp of\na bitter cold wave this morning\nalthough a \u201csnowless blizzard\u201d\nwhich dropped the mercury 50 de\ngrees in three days had abated at\nleast temporarily. 4\nThe official thermometer regist\nered 17 below zero Thursday\nmorning for the coldest reading\nof the winter and was at 15 be\nlow at 10 a. m., although the\nforecast held some promise of re\nlief. \u201cBecoming unsettled, poss\nible snow and rising temperature\u201d\nwas the official guess.\nThe high wind which caused\nminor damage-in numerous places\nchanged the weather almost over-\nnight from what resembled an\nearly spring to a typical Minne\nsota winter. The low temperature\nreading until today was -10 de\ngrees registered Wednesday mor\nning. Skies were clear however\nand the mercury recovered some\nof its loss during the day.\n'While other parts of the state\nwere snow-locked this week, the\nRedwood Falls winter continued\nthe driest in years.\nSo far in January only .14 of\nan inch of moisture has been re\ncorded by N. B. Andersen, official\ncity weatherman. This month last\nyear there, were 1.47 inches of\nmoisture, or well over 10 inches of\nsnow.\nAlthough the total 1937 mois\nture figure of 27.79 is consider\ned normal and is 8.96 inches over\nthose of 1936, the winter months\nof November, December and Jan\nuary of 1937-1938 are 2.45 inches\nof moisture drier than the same\nmonths in 1936-1937. This winter\n1.24 inches of snow and rain fell.\nLast winter there were 3.69 inches\nof moisture.\nComparative figures follow;\nDecember 1937, .98 inches; Decem\nber 1936, 1.5 inches; November\n1937, .72 inches; November 1936,\n.12 inches.\nMoisture figures by the month\nfor the last three years, as com**\npiled by Mr. Andersen are:\n1935 1936 1937\nJanuary\nFebruary 0.43 2.52 71\nMarch MO 2.09 2.07\nApril 3.33 1.10 4.10-\nMay 3.09 3.19 3.46-\nJune 5.64 3.44 5.83;\nJuly 1.44 0.71 2.08\nAugust 2.27 1.82 3.84\nSeptember 0.97 0.73 1.62\nOctober 1.05 0.20 1.51\nNovember 0.85 0.72 0.12\nDecember 0.82 1.50 0.98\n21.99 18.83 27.79\nGRASSHOPPER EGGS\nNOT HURT BY COLD\nThe unusual lack of snow in this\ncommunity this winter will have\nno effect on the grasshdpper crop\nin the spring, according to J. I.\nSwedberg, Redwood county agent.\nGrasshopper eggs are encased in\nthick rubbery cases and are un\naffected by the elements, Mr.\nSwedberg says.\nA cold wet period late in May,\nthe hatching season, would destroy\nmany of the pests, he says.\nFrom a survey of hopper eggs\nin this territory, state entomolo\ngists judge that there will be a\n14 per cent infestation, if all con\nditions are to the advantage of the\ngrasshoppers.\nThe county, however, is pre\npared for a scourge, amply sup\nplied with arsenic bait ordered\nlast year when the infestation\nthreatened to reach serious pro\nportions.\nPONTIAC AGENCY\nTO OPEN APRIL 1\nST. PAUL MAN LEASES\nSPACE IN BURRIS\nBUILDING HERE\nA Pontiac automobile agency\nwill be located in the Burris\nbuilding after April 1, it was an\nnounced Wednesday.\nGeorge A. Anderson who\nbeen in the Pontiac business in\nSt. Paul for about eight years has\nleased the front part of the arcade\nand the office rooms now used by\nthe Burris Body and Paint shop.\nRayburn Burris states that a\nwall will be built to separate the\nautomobile agency rooms now\nused by Burris for car storage\nand the paint shop located at the\nback. The east entrance will be\nused by Burris.\nThe owner of the building will\noccupy the office recently vacated\nby the Schou Land company.\nArrangements for Mr. Ander\nson to take care of car storage in\nthe building have been made. He\nis married and will move hi\u00ab\nfamily here as soon as a house is/\navailable.\nATTEND MEETING\nMr .and Mrs. L. O. Alexander\nand R. W. Whyte motored to Min\nneapolis Saturday to attend the\nI OOF installation at the munici\npal auditorium. They remained\nuntil Sunday and the Alexanders\nI were dinner guests of their son\nGordon at PioocerlMl, returning","height":"25521","width":"20385"}}
